  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "For instance, an analysis of Europarl (Koehn, 2005), one of the more popular training datasets for MT systems, revealed a 2:1 male-female speaker ratio.",
    "Such an imbalanced dataset in terms of male/female representation, most likely implies a higher frequency of male pronouns, male-endings (nouns, adjectives...), increasing the likelihood of generating \"male\" translations when facing ambiguity.",
    "This can be interpreted in the broad way, since there is also evidence that word embeddings are conforming to an overall androcentric worldview (Petreski and Hashim, 2023).",
    "Taking the example below, a few possible translations for the English word 'teacher ' [neutral] are provided in French: 'enseignant' [masculine singular], 'enseignante' [feminine], 'enseignant-e' [binary alternative] or 'le personnel enseignant' [gender-neutral alternative].",
    "5 teacher enseignant enseignante le personnel enseignant enseignant-e Figure 1: Some French translations of the English noun 'teacher'."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For instance, an analysis of Europarl (Koehn, 2005), one of the more popular training datasets for MT systems, revealed a 2:1 male-female speaker ratio.",
    "This can be interpreted in the broad way, since there is also evidence that word embeddings are conforming to an overall androcentric worldview (Petreski and Hashim, 2023).",
    "Taking the example below, a few possible translations for the English word 'teacher ' [neutral] are provided in French: 'enseignant' [masculine singular], 'enseignante' [feminine], 'enseignant-e' [binary alternative] or 'le personnel enseignant' [gender-neutral alternative]."
  ]
